# Contractor Website - High-End Residential Remodeling

## Project Overview
Building a professional website for a general contractor specializing in high-end residential bathroom and kitchen remodels. The site showcases completed work, provides business information, and enables consultation scheduling.

## Tech Stack
- **Framework**: Next.js 15 (App Router)
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS
- **Components**: Shadcn/ui
- **Hosting**: Vercel
- **Image Storage**: Vercel Blob or Cloudinary
- **Scheduling**: Google Calendar integration
- **Email**: Resend or SendGrid
- **Analytics**: Google Analytics or Plausible

## Core Requirements
1. **SEO-first**: Every page must have proper metadata, semantic HTML, structured data
2. **Performance**: Lighthouse score 90+ on all metrics
3. **Responsive**: Mobile-first design, tested on iOS/Android
4. **Accessible**: WCAG 2.1 AA compliance
5. **Fast iteration**: Maintainer-friendly code structure

## Architecture Guidelines

### Directory Structure
```
/app
  /(routes)
    /page.tsx (Home)
    /about/page.tsx
    /gallery/page.tsx
    /schedule/page.tsx
  /api
    /contact/route.ts
    /upload/route.ts (future)
  /layout.tsx
  /globals.css
/components
  /ui (shadcn components)
  /layout (Header, Footer, Nav)
  /gallery (GalleryGrid, Lightbox, ProjectCard)
  /forms (ContactForm, ScheduleForm)
  /home (Hero, Services, CTA)
/lib
  /utils.ts
  /email.ts
  /calendar.ts
  /constants.ts
/public
  /images
  /fonts
```

### Coding Standards
- **TypeScript**: Use strict mode, no `any` types
- **Components**: Server components by default, client components only when needed
- **Naming**: PascalCase for components, camelCase for utilities, kebab-case for routes
- **Imports**: Use absolute imports with `@/` prefix
- **Comments**: Focus on "why" not "what", document complex logic
- **Error handling**: Always handle errors gracefully with user-friendly messages

### Performance Rules
- Use Next.js `<Image>` component for all images
- Implement lazy loading for gallery
- Minimize client-side JavaScript
- Use server actions for form submissions
- Optimize fonts with next/font
- Implement proper caching strategies

### SEO Checklist (Every Page)
- [ ] Unique title tag (50-60 chars)
- [ ] Meta description (150-160 chars)
- [ ] Open Graph tags
- [ ] Twitter Card tags
- [ ] Canonical URL
- [ ] Structured data (JSON-LD)
- [ ] Semantic HTML (h1, h2, nav, main, footer)
- [ ] Alt text for all images

## Phase Implementation

### Phase 1: Foundation ✓
**Goal**: Working Next.js app deployed to Vercel

**Tasks**:
1. Initialize Next.js 15 with TypeScript
   ```bash
   npx create-next-app@latest contractor-site --typescript --tailwind --app
   ```
2. Install dependencies:
   ```bash
   npx shadcn@latest init
   npx shadcn@latest add button card input textarea
   ```
3. Create base layout with Header/Footer
4. Set up environment variables (.env.local)
5. Configure Vercel deployment
6. Implement responsive navigation with mobile menu

**Success Criteria**:
- Site loads on localhost:3000
- Navigation works on mobile/desktop
- Deployed to Vercel with custom domain ready
- TypeScript compiles without errors

### Phase 2: Core Content
**Goal**: Complete informational pages with contact capability

**Tasks**:
1. **Homepage**:
   - Hero section with compelling headline and CTA
   - Services overview (kitchen/bathroom remodeling)
   - Social proof placeholder (testimonials later)
   - High-quality hero image or video background
   
2. **About Page**:
   - Contractor background and expertise
   - Service areas
   - Process/methodology
   - Team information
   
3. **Contact/Schedule Page**:
   - Contact form (name, email, phone, message, project type)
   - Google Calendar scheduling link/widget
   - Business hours and response time expectations
   - Form validation with React Hook Form + Zod
   
4. **Email Integration**:
   - Set up Resend/SendGrid
   - Form submission triggers email to contractor
   - Auto-reply to user confirming receipt

**Success Criteria**:
- All pages accessible via navigation
- Contact form sends emails successfully
- Responsive on mobile, tablet, desktop
- Basic SEO metadata on all pages

### Phase 3: Gallery System
**Goal**: Beautiful, performant photo gallery

**Tasks**:
1. **Gallery Architecture**:
   - Decide: Static images in /public vs. Cloudinary/Vercel Blob
   - Create image upload/management strategy
   - Implement image optimization pipeline
   
2. **Gallery Components**:
   - Responsive grid layout (masonry or CSS grid)
   - Lightbox/modal for full-size viewing
   - Category filters (All, Kitchens, Bathrooms)
   - Project cards with hover effects
   
3. **Features**:
   - Lazy loading with intersection observer
   - Before/after slider component (optional)
   - Project detail modal (optional: description, timeline)
   - Keyboard navigation in lightbox
   
4. **Image Management**:
   - Simple JSON file for gallery data structure
   - Or: Headless CMS integration (Sanity/Contentful) for future scaling

**Data Structure Example**:
```typescript
interface Project {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  category: 'kitchen' | 'bathroom';
  description?: string;
  images: {
    url: string;
    alt: string;
    width: number;
    height: number;
  }[];
  featured?: boolean;
}
```

**Success Criteria**:
- Gallery loads quickly (< 2s on 3G)
- Images are properly optimized
- Smooth user experience on all devices
- Can easily add new projects

### Phase 4: Polish & Launch
**Goal**: Production-ready, optimized site

**Tasks**:
1. **SEO Enhancement**:
   - Add sitemap.xml
   - Add robots.txt
   - Implement structured data (LocalBusiness schema)
   - Add breadcrumbs
   - Optimize meta tags across all pages
   - Add canonical URLs
   
2. **Performance**:
   - Run Lighthouse audit
   - Optimize Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS)
   - Implement proper caching headers
   - Add loading states and skeletons
   - Compress images further if needed
   
3. **Analytics & Monitoring**:
   - Set up Google Analytics or Plausible
   - Implement event tracking (form submissions, calls to action)
   - Add error monitoring (Sentry optional)
   
4. **Final QA**:
   - Cross-browser testing (Chrome, Safari, Firefox)
   - Mobile device testing (iOS, Android)
   - Form validation testing
   - Link checking
   - Spelling and grammar review
   - WCAG accessibility audit

**Success Criteria**:
- Lighthouse scores 90+ (Performance, Accessibility, Best Practices, SEO)
- No console errors
- All forms working
- Analytics tracking conversions
- Google Calendar integration tested

## Future Enhancements (Post-Launch)
- Testimonials section with customer reviews
- Blog for SEO content (remodeling tips, trends)
- Project cost estimator tool
- Service area map with coverage
- Financing information/calculator
- Lead capture with progressive disclosure
- A/B testing on CTAs
- Admin dashboard for gallery management

## Development Workflow
1. Work on feature branch
2. Test locally
3. Commit with descriptive messages
4. Push to trigger Vercel preview deployment
5. Review preview URL
6. Merge to main for production deployment

## Environment Variables Needed
```
# Email
RESEND_API_KEY=
EMAIL_FROM=
EMAIL_TO=

# Google Calendar
GOOGLE_CALENDAR_ID=
GOOGLE_API_KEY=

# Analytics
NEXT_PUBLIC_GA_ID=

# Image Storage (if using Cloudinary)
CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=
CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=
```

## Key Commands
```bash
# Development
npm run dev

# Build
npm run build

# Type check
npm run type-check

# Lint
npm run lint
```

## When Asking Cursor for Help
Be specific about:
- Which phase you're working on
- The component or feature you're implementing
- Any specific requirements (e.g., "mobile-first", "keyboard accessible")
- Desired behavior with examples

Example prompts:
- "Implement the Hero section for Phase 2 with a background image, headline, subheadline, and CTA button. Use Shadcn/ui components."
- "Create a responsive navigation header that collapses to a hamburger menu on mobile."
- "Build a lightbox component for the gallery that supports keyboard navigation and displays image metadata."

## Important Notes
- Always use Server Components unless client interactivity is required
- Prioritize Web Vitals: use next/image, avoid layout shifts
- Test on actual Android device for contractor usability
- Keep the codebase maintainable - you'll be updating this long-term
- Document any non-obvious decisions in code comments